@jlindsey I'm sorry that you feel the process is too difficult for your time. If you're concerned about your personal information, you're free to leave out the address and telephone number from a CLA. 

In many countries, like the United States, your work is automatically copyrighted. Thus the code in you branch that you're offering for merge is actually owned by you and we have no right to it. In most cases, code contributions do not include a license as is true with your license. Because you're offering a patch to source code that is licensed, it is usually implied that you want your copyrighted code to be licensed the same way, but this is not explicit. The CLA makes this explicit.

It also provides a promise that the code you are contributing was yours, and therefore you own the copyright and the legal right to license this copyrighted code under the project's license. In some circumstances, such as if you were writing code on company time, you may not own copyright to your code. A current or past employer who hasn't agreed to allow you to write code and license it publicly on their time might retract that code. Since they owned the copyright, they could. The CLA protects against this by requiring the contributor to vouch that they hold free copyright to their contributions.

